General Linear Models: Count Outcome

Evan Carey, created for BH Analytics

The General Linear Model

  • We can generalize the ordinary linear model to a more flexible framework
  • In regular regression, the predictor variables are on the same scale as the outcome
  • We assume a normal distribution

\[E(X) = B_{0} + B_{1}*X_{1} + B_{2}*X_{2} + ... + B_{k}*X_{k} + e\]

  • A more general framework would be to allow some function to link the predictors to the outcome
  • This is called the link function, and in normal regression it is identity
  • We can also consider different distributional families for the outcome
  • The combination of the link function and the distributional family is the general linear model

Poisson Regression

\[ln(\lambda) = B_{0} + B_{1}*X_{1} + B_{2}*X_{2} + ... + B_{k}*X_{k}\]

  • In Poisson regression, we are modeling a count outcome
  • The distributional family we use is the Poisson distribution, where the mean is equal to the variance
  • The only parameter is therefore lambda (\(\lambda\))
  • The link function is simply log
  • Predictors are on the log scale here

Poisson Regression

  • What is our target of inference in this model?
  • Where is the error term?

The Poisson Distribution

  • You can get a better sense of the Poisson distribution by visualizing the PDF. Considering you can use the dpois() function to map the height of the density at various locations, can you figure out how to make a density for different values of lambda between 0 and 10?

Hint: here is how to do it for lambda = 0.5

x=0:15
y=dpois(x,lambda = 0.5)
library(ggplot2)
qplot(x,y,geom = 'line')

The Poisson Distribution

for (i in c(0.5,1,2,5,10)){
  y=dpois(x,lambda = i)
  print(qplot(x,y,geom = 'line',
              main=paste0('Poisson Distribution with P=',i)))
  }

Null Model

  • The first Poisson model we might fit is the null model, that is a model with only an intercept.
  • What are we predicting here?
library(rstanarm)
CHAINS = 4
SEED = 42

## Run Initial Null Model 
mod0 <- stan_glm(base ~ 1,
                 data=epilepsy,
                 family = poisson(link = "log"),
                 chains=CHAINS, seed=SEED,
                 prior_intercept = normal(0,10))

Assessing model Fit

  • Since we have a posterior distribution that is generative, one way to check the model fit is to generate data from our model, and compare it with the original dataset. We can do this using the pp_check() function.
# Check the model fit
pp_check(mod1)

pp_check(mod1, plotfun='hist')

The Negative Binomial Distribution

  • One solution to the issue of overdispersion is to fit a negative binomial model. This model allows for the variance to be unequal to the mean.
  • This distribution is typically used to describe the number of successes in a sequence until a failure occurs, when the sequence of events are independent and identically distributed Bernoulli trials link
  • In the case of overdispersed count outcomes, we can use the negative binomial distribution to relax the assumption of mean equals Variance in the Poisson.
## fit negative binomial 
mod0nb <- stan_glm(base ~ 1,
                 data=epilepsy,
                 family = neg_binomial_2(link = 'log'),
                 prior_intercept = normal(0,10),
                 prior_aux = cauchy(0,5), 
                 chains=CHAINS, seed=SEED)

##                       mcse  Rhat  n_eff

## For each parameter, mcse is Monte Carlo standard error, n_eff is a crude measure of effective sample size, and Rhat is the potential scale reduction factor on split chains (at convergence Rhat=1).
  • Considering this is a log link function, we can interpret the coefficients similarly as we did in the Poisson regression. In the case of this intercept only model, we can exponentiate the intercept to get the expected count (mean) for the data.
coef(mod0nb)
## (Intercept) 
##    3.440905
exp(coef(mod0nb))
## (Intercept) 
##     31.2152

Assessing model Fit

  • Since we have a posterior distribution that is generative, one way to check the model fit is to generate data from our model, and compare it with the original dataset. We can do this using the pp_check() function.

Multivariate Negative Binomial

  • Let’s say we are interested in checking to see if there was any difference in the baseline seizure rate across our treatment groups, as this would indicate a source of bias in the study.

  • We can proceed with our model as we typically do in R, adding predictors via the formula

## fit negative binomial with treatment
mod1nb <- stan_glm(base ~ treatment,
                 data=epilepsy,
                 family = neg_binomial_2(link = 'log'),
                 prior_intercept = normal(0,10),
                 prior_aux = cauchy(0,5), 
                 chains=CHAINS, seed=SEED)

Predicting Outcomes for Patients

  • Here are the model results, and the corresponding exponentiated parameters.
exp(coef(mod1nb))
##        (Intercept) treatmentProgabide 
##          30.772095           1.027855
exp(posterior_interval(mod1nb))
##                               5%       95%
## (Intercept)           27.5702409 34.489981
## treatmentProgabide     0.8808376  1.207429
## reciprocal_dispersion  5.4937972  9.990342

  • We can interpret this as the following: ‘Patients assigned to the treatment group had on average 2.7% more seizures at baseline, however, the 95% credibility interval includes 0 (0.88 to 1.2)’.

  • How can we get the actual expected number for treatment and placebo patients? You could do the math on the above estimates and include the intercept….but we have the posterior! So let’s just summarize the posterior accordingly.

df1 <- data.frame(treatment=c('Progabide', 'placebo'))
# Get estimates on the scale of the outcome with Transform=T
df1_posterior <- posterior_epred(mod1nb,newdata = df1)
colnames(df1_posterior) <- c('Progabide', 'placebo')
apply(df1_posterior,2, quantile, probs=c(0.05,0.5,0.95))
##      
##       Progabide  placebo
##   5%   28.40240 27.57024
##   50%  31.67903 30.77210
##   95%  35.29227 34.48998
